# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bernie-sanders
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] The **102nd United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1991, to January 3, 1993, during the last two years of George H.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress where Republicans held a Senate seat from California.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in this House of Representatives was based on the 1980 United States census.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] Both chambers maintained a Democratic majority.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p01] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p02] Lists of committees and their party leaders for members of the House and Senate committees can be found through the Official Congressional Directory at the bottom of this article.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p02] The directory after the pages of terms of service lists committees of the Senate, House (Standing with Subcommittees, Select and Special) and Joint and, after that, House/Senate committee assignments.
[src:bernie-sanders/102nd-united-states-congress-p02] On the committees section of the House and Senate in the Official Congressional Directory, the committee's members on the first row on the left side shows the chairman of the committee and on the right side shows the ranking member of the committee.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] The **103rd United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C. from January 3, 1993, to January 3, 1995, during the final weeks of George H.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Bush's presidency and in the first two years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress to have a Democratic senator from Texas, Bob Krueger, who lost election to finish Lloyd Bentsen's term in 1993.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Along with two Democratic senators from the state of Tennessee, Jim Sasser and Harlan Mathews.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Jim Sasser lost re-election and Harlan Mathews retired in 1994.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] In addition, a Democratic senator from the state of Oklahoma, David Boren, resigned in the final weeks of the Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Both chambers maintained a Democratic majority, and with Bill Clinton being sworn in as president on January 20, 1993, this gave the Democrats an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 96th Congress in 1979.
[src:bernie-sanders/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] The **104th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from January 3, 1995, to January 3, 1997, during the third and fourth years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] Apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had Republican majorities for the first time since the 83rd Congress in 1953.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] Major events included passage of elements of the Contract with America and a budget impasse between Congress and the Clinton administration that resulted in the federal government shutdown of 1995 and 1996.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1996; Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1998; and Class 1 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 2000.
[src:bernie-sanders/104th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] The **105th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, DC from January 3, 1997, to January 3, 1999, during the fifth and sixth years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] This is the most recent Congress with a Republican senator from New York, Al D'Amato, who lost re-election in 1998, and a Democratic senator from Kentucky, Wendell Ford, who retired at the end of the Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] Both chambers retained a Republican majority.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] President Clinton was impeached by the US House of Representatives of the 105th Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] There was no change in the parties during this Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, facing re-election in 1998; Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, facing re-election in 2000; and Class 2 meant their term began in this Congress, facing re-election in 2002.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] Representatives are listed by districts.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] There were no changes in Senate membership during this Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/105th-united-states-congress] Four members of the House of Representatives died, and four resigned.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] The **106th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1999, to January 3, 2001, during the last two years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] Both chambers maintained a Republican majority.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] This is the most recent Congress with Republican senators from the states of Delaware (William Roth), Michigan (Spencer Abraham) and Washington (Slade Gorton), all of whom lost re-election in 2000.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] It was the first Congress where Baby boomers comprised the majority of the House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] There were two resignations and three deaths.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, facing re-election in 2000; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, facing re-election in 2002; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, facing re-election in 2004.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] In October 2000, the United States Congress passed a Sense of Congress resolution that McVay's record should reflect that "he is exonerated for the loss of the USS Indianapolis." President Clinton also signed the resolution, which rightented the miscarriage of justice on Charles B.
[src:bernie-sanders/106th-united-states-congress] McVay III for the sinking of the USS Indianapolis in 30 July 1945 by Japanese submarine I-58 (1943).
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] The **107th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 2001, to January 3, 2003, during the final weeks of the Clinton presidency and the first two years of the George W.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in this House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] The House of Representatives had a Republican majority throughout the session, while the Senate was tied 50–50 for only the second time in history resulting in numerous changes in the majority.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] Vice President Al Gore gave Democrats a majority for 17 days, then a Republican majority after Dick Cheney became Vice President on January 20, 2001.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] Senator Jim Jeffords (R-VT) became an independent who caucused with the Democrats on June 6, 2001, giving the party a 51–49 majority for the rest of the Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] When Bush was sworn in as president on January 20, the Republicans held a federal trifecta for the first time since the 83rd Congress in 1955.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] A rare even split in the United States Senate, the defection of a Senator, and the inauguration of a new Vice President, led to *three* changes in majorities.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, facing re-election in 2002; Class 3 meant their term began in the previous Congress, facing re-election in 2004; and Class 1 meant their term began in this Congress, facing re-election in 2006.
[src:bernie-sanders/107th-united-states-congress] Congressional district numbers are linked to articles describing the district itself.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] The **108th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives from January 3, 2003, to January 3, 2005, during the third and fourth years of George W.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] House members were elected in the 2002 general election on November 5, 2002.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected in three classes in the 1998 general election on November 3, 1998, 2000 general election on November 7, 2000, or 2002 general election on November 5, 2002.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 2000 United States census.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] This is the most recent Congress to have a Democratic senator from South Carolina, Fritz Hollings, who retired at the end of the Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Republican majority, with the Republicans slightly increasing their edge in the House, and regaining control of the Senate, after party control had switched back and forth during the 107th Congress due to various factors.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] With President Bush, this gave the Republicans an overall federal government trifecta.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] The party summary for the Senate remained the same during the entire 108th Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] Due to resignations and special elections, Republicans lost a net of two seats to the Democrats.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] All seats were filled though special elections.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] Senators are preceded by the class, In this Congress, Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 2004; Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 2006; and Class 2 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring reelection in 2008.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] Representatives are preceded by the district number.
[src:bernie-sanders/108th-united-states-congress] Members who came and left during this Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Born into a working-class Jewish family and raised in New York City, Sanders attended Brooklyn College before graduating from the University of Chicago in 1964.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] While a student, he was a protest organizer for the Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) during the civil rights movement.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After settling in Vermont in 1968, he ran unsuccessful third-party political campaigns in the 1970s.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He was elected mayor of Burlington in 1981 as an independent and was reelected three times.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was elected to the United States House of Representatives in 1990, representing Vermont's at-large congressional district.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1991, he and five other House members co-founded the Congressional Progressive Caucus.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was a U.S. representative for 16 years before being elected to the U.S.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Senate in 2006, becoming the first non-Republican elected to Vermont's Class 1 seat since Solomon Foot, a Whig, in 1850.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders also chaired the Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee from 2013 to 2015, the Senate Budget Committee from 2021 to 2023, and the Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee from 2023 to 2025.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He is the senior senator and dean of the Vermont congressional delegation.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was a candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination in 2016 and 2020, finishing second both times.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His 2016 campaign generated significant grassroots enthusiasm and funding from small-dollar donors, helping him win 23 primaries and caucuses.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2020, his strong showing in early primaries and caucuses made him the front-runner in a large field of Democratic candidates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He became a close ally of Joe Biden after the 2020 primaries.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Since Donald Trump's reelection in 2024, Sanders has vocally opposed Trump's second administration and what he describes as a right-wing oligarchy, organizing rallies against Trump and his allies, especially Elon Musk, as part of an effort to reshape the Democratic Party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders is credited with influencing a leftward shift in the Democratic Party after his 2016 campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] An advocate of progressive policies, he opposes neoliberalism and authoritarianism.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He supports workers' self-management, universal and single-payer healthcare, paid parental leave, tuition-free tertiary education, a Green New Deal, and worker control of production through cooperatives, unions, and democratic public enterprises.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On foreign policy, he supports reducing military spending, more diplomacy and international cooperation, and greater emphasis on labor rights and environmental concerns in negotiating international trade agreements.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders supports workplace democracy and has praised elements of the Nordic model.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Bernard Sanders was born on September 8, 1941, in the New York City borough of Brooklyn.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His father, Elias Ben Yehuda Sanders, a Polish-Jewish immigrant, was born in Słopnice, a town in Austrian Galicia that was then part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire and is now in Poland.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Elias Sanders immigrated to the United States in 1921 and became a paint salesman.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Bernie's mother, Dorothy Sanders (née Glassberg), was born in New York City.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders says he became interested in politics at an early age due to his family background.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In the 1940s, many of his relatives in German-occupied Poland were murdered in the Holocaust.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] 197, where he won a borough championship on the basketball team.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He attended Hebrew school in the afternoons and celebrated his bar mitzvah in 1954.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His older brother Larry said that during their childhood, the family never lacked food or clothing, but major purchases, "like curtains or a rug", were not affordable.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders attended James Madison High School, where he was captain of the track team and took third place in the New York City indoor one-mile race.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In high school, he lost his first election, finishing last of three candidates for the student body presidency with a campaign that focused on aiding Korean War orphans.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Despite the loss, he became active in his school's fundraising activities for Korean orphans, including organizing a charity basketball game.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders attended high school with economist Walter Block.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] When he was 19, his mother died at age 47.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His father died two years later, in 1962, at age 57.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders studied at Brooklyn College for a year in 1959–1960 before transferring to the University of Chicago and graduating with a Bachelor of Arts degree in political science in 1964.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In later interviews, Sanders described himself as a mediocre college student because the classroom was "boring and irrelevant" and said he viewed community activism as more important to his education.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Under his chairmanship, the university chapter of CORE merged with the university chapter of the SNCC.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In January 1962, he went to a rally at the University of Chicago administration building to protest university president George Wells Beadle's segregated campus housing policy.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] At the protest, Sanders said, "We feel it is an intolerable situation when Negro and white students of the university cannot live together in university-owned apartments." He and 32 other students then entered the building and camped outside the president's office.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After weeks of sit-ins, Beadle and the university formed a commission to investigate discrimination.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After further protests, the University of Chicago ended racial segregation in private university housing in the summer of 1963.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Joan Mahoney, a member of the University of Chicago CORE chapter at the time and a fellow participant in the sit-ins, described Sanders in a 2016 interview as "a swell guy, a nice Jewish boy from Brooklyn, but he wasn't terribly charismatic.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] One of his strengths, though, was his ability to work with a wide group of people, even those he didn't agree with." Sanders once spent a day putting up fliers protesting police brutality, only to notice later that Chicago police had shadowed him and taken them all down.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He attended the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, where Martin Luther King Jr. gave the "I Have a Dream" speech.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] That summer, Sanders was fined $25 (equivalent to $263 in 2025) for resisting arrest during a demonstration in Englewood against segregation in Chicago's public schools.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In addition to his civil rights activism during the 1960s and 1970s, Sanders was active in several peace and antiwar movements while attending the University of Chicago, becoming a member of the Student Peace Union.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He applied for conscientious objector status during the Vietnam War; his application was eventually turned down, by which point he was too old to be drafted.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Although he opposed the war, Sanders never criticized those who fought in it and has strongly supported veterans' benefits throughout his political career.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He was briefly an organizer with the United Packinghouse Workers of America while in Chicago.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He also worked on the reelection campaign of Leon Despres, a prominent Chicago alderman who opposed then mayor Richard J.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After graduating from college, Sanders returned to New York City, where he worked various jobs, including Head Start teacher, psychiatric aide, and carpenter.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1968, he moved to Stannard, Vermont, a town small in both area and population (88 residents at the 1970 census) within Vermont's rural Northeast Kingdom region, because he had been "captivated by rural life".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] While there, he worked as a carpenter, filmmaker, and writer who created and sold "radical film strips" and other educational materials to schools.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders wrote articles for *The Vermont Freeman*.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] One article later received media attention during his national political career after its contents were rediscovered and reported in the press.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He lived in the area for several years before moving to the more populous Chittenden County in the mid-1970s.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During his 2018 reelection campaign, he returned to the town to hold an event with voters and other candidates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] From 1969 to 1971, Sanders resided in Montpelier.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After moving to Burlington, he began his electoral political career as a member of the Liberty Union Party, a national umbrella party for various socialist-oriented state parties, originating in the anti-war movement and the People's Party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He ran as the Liberty Union candidate for governor of Vermont in 1972 and 1976 and as a candidate in the special election for U.S. senator in 1972 and in the general election in 1974.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In the 1974 senatorial race, he finished third (5,901 votes; 4%), behind 34-year-old Chittenden County state's attorney Patrick Leahy (D; 70,629 votes; 49%) and two-term incumbent U.S.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Representative Dick Mallary (R; 66,223 votes; 46%).
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1971, while researching an article for Liberty Union's newspaper *Movement*, Sanders stayed at Myrtle Hill Farm, a Vermont back to the land commune.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He was asked to leave after three days for failing to contribute physical labor expected of all members.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Some residents complained that Sanders spent his time engaging others in political discussions, distracting them from their work, with one member claiming the only way "any work was going to get accomplished" was if people were pulled out of Sanders's orbit.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The 1976 campaign was the zenith of the Liberty Union's influence, with Sanders collecting 11,317 votes for governor and the party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His strong performance forced the down-ballot races for lieutenant governor and secretary of state to be decided by the state legislature when its vote total prevented either the Republican or Democratic candidate for those offices from garnering a majority of votes.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] But the campaign drained the Liberty Union's finances and energy, and in October 1977, Sanders and the Liberty Union candidate for attorney general, Nancy Kaufman, announced their retirement from the party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During the 1980 presidential election, Sanders was one of three electors for the Socialist Workers Party in Vermont.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After resigning from the Liberty Union Party in 1977, Sanders worked as a writer and as the director of the nonprofit American People's Historical Society (APHS).
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] While with the APHS, he produced a 30-minute documentary about American labor leader Eugene V.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Debs, who ran for president five times as the Socialist Party candidate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Debs Foundation gave Sanders its namesake award, first given to John L.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On November 8, 1980, Sanders announced his candidacy for mayor.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He formally announced his campaign on December 16 at a City Hall press conference.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders selected Linda Niedweske as his campaign manager.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The Citizens Party attempted to nominate Greg Guma for mayor, but Guma declined, saying it would be "difficult to run against another progressive candidate".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders initially won the mayoral election by 22 votes against incumbent mayor Gordon Paquette, Richard Bove, and Joseph McGrath, but the margin was later reduced to 10 votes.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Paquette did not contest the results of the recount.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Paquette's loss was attributed to his own shortcomings, as he did not campaign or promote his candidacy since neither Sanders nor Bove was seen as a serious challenger.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders had not previously won an election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Paquette was also considered to have lost because he proposed an unpopular $0.65 per $100 raise in taxes that Sanders opposed.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders spent around $4,000 on his campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders criticized the pro-development incumbent as an ally of prominent shopping center developer Antonio Pomerleau, while Paquette warned of ruin for Burlington if Sanders were elected.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The Sanders campaign was bolstered by a wave of optimistic volunteers as well as a series of endorsements from university professors, social welfare agencies, and the police union.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The result shocked the local political establishment.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders formed a coalition of independents and the Citizens Party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On December 3, 1982, he announced that he would seek reelection.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On January 22, 1983, the Citizens Party voted unanimously to endorse Sanders, although Sanders ran as an independent.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He was reelected, defeating Judy Stephany and James Gilson.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders initially considered not seeking a third term, but announced on December 5, 1984, that he would run.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He formally launched his campaign on December 7 and was reelected.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On December 1, 1986, Sanders, who had finished third in the 1986 Vermont gubernatorial election, announced that he would seek reelection to a fourth term as mayor of Burlington, despite close associates saying that he was tired of being mayor.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders defeated Democratic nominee Paul Lafayette in the election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He said he would not seek another mayoral term after the 1987 election: "eight years is enough and I think it is time for new leadership, which does exist within the coalition, to come up".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders did not run for a fifth term as mayor.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He went on to lecture in political science at Harvard Kennedy School that year and at Hamilton College in 1991.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During his mayoralty, Sanders called himself a socialist and was described as such in the press.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During his first term, his supporters, including the first Citizens Party city councilor Terry Bouricius, formed the Progressive Coalition, the forerunner of the Vermont Progressive Party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The Progressives never held more than six seats on the 13-member city council, but they had enough to keep the council from overriding Sanders's vetoes.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As mayor, Sanders also led extensive downtown revitalization projects.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] One of his primary achievements was improving Burlington's Lake Champlain waterfront.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1981, he campaigned against the unpopular plans by Burlington developer Tony Pomerleau to convert the then-industrial waterfront property owned by the Central Vermont Railway into expensive condominiums, hotels, and offices.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He ran under the slogan "Burlington is not for sale" and successfully supported a plan that redeveloped the waterfront area into a mixed-use district featuring housing, parks, and public spaces.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was a consistent critic of US foreign policy in Latin America throughout the 1980s.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1985, Burlington City Hall hosted a foreign policy speech by Noam Chomsky.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In his introduction, he praised Chomsky as "a very vocal and important voice in the wilderness of intellectual life in America" and said that he was "delighted to welcome a person who I think we're all very proud of".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders hosted and produced a public-access television program, *Bernie Speaks with the Community*, from 1986 to 1988.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He collaborated with 30 Vermont musicians to record a folk album, *We Shall Overcome*, in 1987.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] That same year, *US News & World Report* ranked Sanders one of America's best mayors.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As of 2013, Burlington was regarded as one of the most livable cities in the United States.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During a trip to the Soviet Union in 1988, Sanders interviewed the mayor of Burlington's sister city Yaroslavl about housing and health care issues in the two cities.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] When Sanders left office in 1989, Bouricius, a member of the Burlington city council, said that Sanders had "changed the entire nature of politics in Burlington and also in the state of Vermont".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1988, incumbent Republican congressman Jim Jeffords decided to run for the U.S.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Senate, vacating the House seat representing Vermont's at-large congressional district.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Smith won the House election with a plurality, securing 41% of the vote.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders, who ran as an independent, placed second with 38% of the vote, while Democratic state representative Paul N.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Two years later, he ran for the seat again and defeated Smith by a margin of 56% to 39%.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was the first independent elected to the U.S.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] House of Representatives since Frazier Reams of Ohio won his second term in 1952, as well as the first socialist elected to the House since Vito Marcantonio, from the American Labor Party, who won his last term in 1948.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was a representative from 1991 until he became a senator in 2007, winning reelection by large margins except during the 1994 Republican Revolution, when he won by 3%, with 50% of the vote.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During his first year in the House, Sanders often alienated allies and colleagues with his criticism of both political parties as working primarily on behalf of the wealthy.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1991, he co-founded the Congressional Progressive Caucus, a group of mostly liberal Democrats that he chaired for its first eight years, while still refusing to join the Democratic Party or caucus.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2005, *Rolling Stone* called Sanders the "amendment king" for his ability to get more roll call amendments passed than any other congressman during the period since 1995, when Congress was entirely under Republican control.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Being an independent allowed him to form coalitions across party lines.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1999, Sanders voted and advocated against rolling back the Glass–Steagall legislation provisions that kept investment banks and commercial banks separate entities.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Concerned by high breast cancer rates in Vermont, on February 7, 1992, Sanders sponsored the Cancer Registries Amendment Act to establish cancer registries to collect data on cancer.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Senator Patrick Leahy introduced a companion bill in the Senate on October 2, 1992.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The Senate bill was passed by the House on October 6 and signed into law by President George H.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1993, Sanders voted against the Brady Bill, which mandated federal background checks when buying guns and imposed a waiting period on firearm purchasers in the United States; the bill passed by a vote of 238–187.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He voted against the bill four more times in the 1990s, explaining that his Vermont constituents saw waiting-period mandates as more appropriately a state rather than a federal matter.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders did vote for other gun-control measures.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] For example, in 1994, he voted for the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act "because it included the Violence Against Women Act and the ban on certain assault weapons." He was nevertheless critical of the other parts of the bill.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders has at times favored stronger law enforcement and sentencing.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1996, he voted against a bill that would have prohibited police from purchasing tanks and armored carriers.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 1998, he voted for a bill that would have increased minimum sentencing for possessing a gun while committing a federal crime to ten years in prison, including nonviolent crimes such as marijuana possession.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2005, Sanders voted for the Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The purpose of the act was to prevent firearms manufacturers and dealers from being held liable for negligence when crimes have been committed with their products.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As of 2016, he said that he has since changed his position and would vote for legislation to defeat this bill.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was a consistent critic of the Patriot Act.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As a member of Congress, he voted against the original Patriot Act legislation.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After its 357–66 passage in the House, he sponsored and voted for several subsequent amendments and acts attempting to curtail its effects and voted against each reauthorization.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In June 2005, he proposed an amendment to limit Patriot Act provisions that allow the government to obtain individuals' library and book-buying records.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The amendment passed the House by a bipartisan majority but was removed on November 4 of that year in House–Senate negotiations and never became law.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders voted against the resolutions authorizing the use of force against Iraq in 1991 and 2002, and he opposed the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He voted for the 2001 Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists that has been cited as the legal justification for controversial military actions since the September 11 attacks.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He especially opposed the Bush administration's decision to start a war unilaterally.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In February 2005, Sanders introduced a bill that would have withdrawn the permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) status that had been extended to China in October 2000.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He said to the House, "Anyone who takes an objective look at our trade policy with China must conclude that it is an absolute failure and needs to be fundamentally overhauled", citing the American jobs being lost to overseas competitors.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His bill received 71 co-sponsors but was not sent to the floor for a vote.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Senate on April 21, 2005, after Senator Jim Jeffords announced that he would not seek a fourth term.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Chuck Schumer, chair of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee and fellow James Madison High School alumnus, endorsed Sanders.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] This was a critical move because it meant no Democrat running against him could expect financial help from the party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He was also endorsed by Senate minority leader Harry Reid and Democratic National Committee chair and former Vermont governor Howard Dean.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Dean said in May 2005 that he considered Sanders an ally who "votes with the Democrats 98% of the time".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Then-Senator Barack Obama also campaigned for him in Vermont in March 2006.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders entered into an agreement with the Democratic Party, much as he had as a congressman, to be listed in their primary but to decline the nomination should he win, which he did.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In the most expensive political campaign in Vermont's history, Sanders defeated businessman Rich Tarrant by an almost 2-to-1 margin.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Many national media outlets projected him as the winner just after the polls closed, before any returns came in.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was reelected in 2012 with 71% of the vote, defeating Republican nominee John MacGovern.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was reelected in 2018 with 67% of the vote, defeating real estate broker and Republican nominee Lawrence Zupan.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On May 6, 2024, Sanders announced his candidacy for a fourth Senate term.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] A poll just a few weeks earlier found that more than half of respondents wanted him to seek reelection.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders faced Republican nominee Gerald Malloy, who ran against Senator Peter Welch in 2022.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was reelected and has said this term will likely be his last.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] While a member of Congress, Sanders sponsored 15 concurrent resolutions and 15 Senate resolutions.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Of those he co-sponsored, 218 became law.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] While he has consistently advocated for progressive causes, *Politico* wrote that he has "rarely forged actual legislation or left a significant imprint on it".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] According to *The New York Times*, "Big legislation largely eludes Mr.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders because his ideas are usually far to the left of the majority of the Senate ...
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Nevertheless, he has sponsored over 500 amendments to bills, many of which became law.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In August 2022, Sanders voted for the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He was not satisfied with the bill, calling it only a small step forward.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders joined with Democrats to pass the Inflation Reduction Act, which capped the cost of insulin for seniors on Medicare to $35 a month and allowed Medicare to negotiate lower drug prices.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2008 and 2009, Sanders voted against the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP), a program to purchase toxic banking assets and provide loans to banks that were in free-fall.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On February 4, 2009, he sponsored an amendment to ensure that TARP funds would not displace US workers.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The amendment passed and was added to the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On December 10, 2010, Sanders delivered an 8-hour and 34-minute speech against the Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010, which proposed extending the Bush-era tax rates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He argued that the legislation would favor the wealthiest Americans.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Nevertheless, the bill passed the Senate with a strong majority and was signed into law a week later.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In February 2011, Nation Books published the speech as *The Speech: A Historic Filibuster on Corporate Greed and the Decline of Our Middle Class*, with authorial proceeds going to Vermont nonprofit charitable organizations.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2016, Sanders voted for the Federal Reserve Transparency Act, which included proposals for a reformed audit of the Federal Reserve System.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On June 12, 2017, U.S. senators agreed to legislation imposing new sanctions on Russia and Iran.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The bill was opposed only by Sanders and Republican Rand Paul.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He supported the sanctions on Russia, but voted against the bill because he believed the sanctions could endanger the Iran nuclear deal.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] After the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi in October 2018 (which was ordered by Saudi Arabian crown prince Mohammad bin Salman, according to multiple intelligence agencies), his bill attracted bipartisan co-sponsors and support, and the Senate passed it by a vote of 56–41.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] During the Gaza war, Sanders introduced several Joint Resolutions of Disapproval to block arms to Israel.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] All failed, but some Democrats voted for them.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In November 2024, one such resolution garnered support from 18 senators.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In April 2025, 15 senators supported another.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In July 2025, 27 senators supported a resolution, a majority of Senate Democrats.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In mid-December 2009, Sanders successfully added a provision to the Affordable Care Act to fund $11 billion to community health centers, especially those in rural areas.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The provision brought together Democrats on the left with Democrats from conservative, rural areas, helping to secure the 60 votes needed for passage.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On May 4, 2017, in response to the House vote to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act, he predicted "thousands of Americans would die" from no longer having access to health care.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] PolitiFact rated his statement "mostly true".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In September 2017, Sanders along with 15 Senate co-sponsors submitted the Medicare for All bill, a single-payer healthcare plan.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The bill covers vision and dental care, unlike Medicare.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Primary Health and Aging, Sanders introduced legislation in 2013 to reauthorize and strengthen the Older Americans Act, which supports Meals on Wheels and other programs for seniors.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2007, Sanders helped kill a bill introducing comprehensive immigration reform, arguing that its guest-worker program would depress wages for American workers.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2010, he supported the DREAM Act, which would have provided a path to citizenship for undocumented immigrants who had been brought to the United States as minors.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2013, he supported the Gang of Eight's comprehensive immigration reform bill after securing a $1.5 billion youth jobs program provision, which he argued would offset the harm of labor market competition with immigrants.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In April 2017, Sanders introduced a bill that would raise the minimum wage for federal contract workers to $15 an hour, an increase over an earlier Democratic $12 an hour proposal.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On May 9, 2018, he introduced the Workplace Democracy Act, a bill that would expand labor rights by making it easier for workers to join a union, ban right-to-work laws and some anti-union provisions of the Taft–Hartley Act, and outlaw some union-busting tactics.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On September 5, 2018, Sanders partnered with Ro Khanna to introduce the Stop Bad Employers by Zeroing Out Subsidies (Stop BEZOS) Act, which would require large corporations to pay for the food stamps and Medicaid benefits that their employees receive, relieving the burden on taxpayers.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On June 9, 2014, Sanders sponsored the Veterans' Access to Care through Choice, Accountability, and Transparency Act of 2014 to reform the Department of Veterans Affairs in the wake of the Veterans Health Administration scandal of 2014.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He worked with Senator John McCain, who co-sponsored the bill.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His bill was incorporated into the House version of the bill, which passed both chambers on July 31, 2014, and was signed into law by President Obama on August 7, 2014.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] On March 17, 2016, Sanders said he would support Merrick Garland's nomination to the Supreme Court, though he added, "there are some more progressive judges out there." He opposed Neil Gorsuch's nomination to the court, saying that Gorsuch had "refused to answer legitimate questions".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He also objected to Senate Republicans' use of the nuclear option to "choke off debate and ram [Gorsuch's] nomination through the Senate".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He voted against Gorsuch's confirmation as an associate justice and against Trump's nominees Brett Kavanaugh and Amy Coney Barrett.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2022, Sanders voted to confirm Joe Biden's nominee Ketanji Brown Jackson to the Supreme Court.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As an independent, Sanders maintains an agreement with the Senate Democratic leadership where he votes with the Democrats on all procedural matters unless the Democratic whip, Dick Durbin, agrees that he need not (a request rarely made or granted).
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In return he was allowed to keep his seniority and received the committee seats that would have been available to him as a Democrat; in 2013–14 he was chairman of the United States Senate Committee on Veterans' Affairs (during the Veterans Health Administration scandal).
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders became the ranking minority member on the Senate Budget Committee in 2015 and the chair in 2021; he previously chaired the Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee for two years.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Since 2017, he has been chair of the Senate Democratic Outreach Committee.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Sanders was only the third senator from Vermont to caucus with the Democrats, after Jeffords and Leahy.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] His caucusing with the Democrats gave them a 51–49 majority in the Senate during the 110th Congress in 2007–08.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] The Democrats needed 51 seats to control the Senate because Vice President Dick Cheney would likely have broken potential ties in favor of the Republicans.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Polling conducted in August 2011 by Public Policy Polling found that Sanders's approval rating was 67% and his disapproval rating 28%, making him then the third-most popular US senator.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] Both the NAACP (National Association for the Advancement of Colored People) and the NHLA (National Hispanic Leadership Agenda) have given him 100% voting scores during his tenure in the Senate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In 2015, he was named one of the Top 5 of *The Forward* 50.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In a November 2015 Morning Consult poll, he reached an 83% approval rating among his constituents, making him the most popular US senator.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] As of 2026, polling by the Morning Consult found Sanders was still the most popular U.S. senator, with 68% approval among Vermont voters.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In March 2017, Fox News found him to have the highest net favorability of any prominent politician included in its poll, at +28 points.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] He ranked third in 2014 and first in both 2015 and 2016.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p01] In April 2017, a nationwide Harvard-Harris Poll found that Sanders had the highest favorability rating of any political figure included in the poll, a standing confirmed by subsequent polling.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] During the 2012 Democratic presidential primaries, Sanders—dissatisfied with President Obama's "attempts to trade Social Security cuts for tax hikes"—reportedly considered running against him in the primaries.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He added that if no progressive candidate ran, he might feel compelled to do so himself.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In December 2014, Warren said she was not running.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders announced his intention to seek the Democratic Party's nomination for president on April 30, 2015.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His campaign was officially launched on May 26 in Burlington.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In his announcement, Sanders said, "I don't believe that the men and women who defended American democracy fought to create a situation where billionaires own the political process" and made this a central idea throughout his campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Warren welcomed Sanders's entry into the race, saying, "I'm glad to see him get out there and give his version of what leadership in this country should be", but never endorsed him.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Initially considered a long shot, Sanders won 23 primaries and caucuses and around 46% of pledged delegates to Hillary Clinton's 54%.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His campaign was noted for its supporters' enthusiasm, as well as for rejecting large donations from corporations, the financial industry, and any associated Super PAC.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Some of the Democratic National Committee (DNC) emails leaked to the public in June and July 2016 showed that the committee leadership had favored Clinton over him and had worked to help Clinton win the nomination.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On July 12, 2016, Sanders formally endorsed Clinton in her unsuccessful general election campaign against Republican Donald Trump, while urging his supporters to continue the "political revolution" his campaign had begun.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Following his endorsement, Sanders spent weeks campaigning for Clinton, holding 39 rallies in 13 states during the final three months before the 2016 election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Unlike the other major candidates, Sanders did not pursue funding through a Super PAC or from wealthy donors, instead focusing on small-dollar donations.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His presidential campaign raised $1.5 million within 24 hours of his official announcement.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] At the end of the year, the campaign had raised a total of $73 million from more than one million people, making 2.5 million donations, with an average donation of $27.16.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The campaign reached 3.25 million donations by the end of January 2016, raising $20 million in that month alone.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders used social media to help his campaign gain momentum, posting content to online platforms such as Twitter and Facebook and answering questions on Reddit.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He gained a large grassroots organizational following online.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] A July 29, 2015, meetup organized online brought 100,000 supporters to more than 3,500 simultaneous events nationwide.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] To his surprise, Sanders's June 2015 campaign events drew overflow crowds across the country.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] When Clinton and Sanders made public appearances within days of each other in Des Moines, Iowa, he drew larger crowds, even though he had already made many stops around the state and Clinton's visit was her first in 2015.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On July 1, 2015, his campaign stop in Madison, Wisconsin, drew the largest crowd of any 2016 presidential candidate to that date, with an estimated turnout of 10,000.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Over the following weeks, he drew even larger crowds: 11,000 in Phoenix; 15,000 in Seattle; and 28,000 in Portland, Oregon.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The Democratic National Committee (DNC) announced in May 2015 that there would be six debates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Critics alleged that the small number of debates and the schedule, with half of the debates on Saturday or Sunday nights, were part of the DNC's deliberate attempt to protect Clinton, who was perceived as the front-runner.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In February 2016, both the Clinton and Sanders campaigns agreed in principle to holding four more debates for a total of ten.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Clinton dropped out of the tenth debate, scheduled to take place just before the California primary, citing a need to devote her time to making direct contact with California voters and preparing for the general election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Some Sanders supporters raised concerns that publications such as *The New York Times* minimized coverage of the Sanders campaign in favor of other candidates, especially Trump and Clinton.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The *Times*' ombudsman reviewed her paper's coverage of the Sanders campaign and found that as of September 2015 the *Times* "hasn't always taken it very seriously.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The tone of some stories is regrettably dismissive, even mocking at times.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] A December 2015 report found that the three major networks—CBS, NBC, and ABC—had spent 234 minutes reporting on Trump and 10 minutes on Sanders, despite their similar polling results.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The report noted that *ABC World News Tonight* had spent 81 minutes on Trump and less than one minute on Sanders during 2015.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Studies concluded that the tone of media coverage of Sanders was more favorable than that of any other candidate, whereas his main opponent in the Democratic primary, Hillary Clinton, received the most negative coverage of any candidate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] All 2016 candidates received vastly less media coverage than Donald Trump, and the Democratic primary received substantially less coverage than the Republican primary.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Amy Goodman of *Democracy Now!* noted that on March 15, Super Tuesday III, the speeches of Trump, Clinton, Marco Rubio, and Ted Cruz were broadcast in full.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders was in Phoenix, Arizona, on that date, speaking to a rally larger than any of the others, yet his speech was not mentioned, let alone broadcast.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] An NBC/*Wall Street Journal* poll conducted in May 2016 found Clinton and Trump (by then the presumptive Republican nominee) in a "dead heat", but the same poll found that if Sanders were the Democratic nominee, 53% of voters would support him to 39% for Trump.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Clinton and Trump were the least popular likely candidates ever polled, while Sanders received a 43% positive, 36% negative rating.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Polls showed that Democratic voters older than 50 preferred Clinton by a large margin but that those under 50 overwhelmingly favored Sanders.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] A 2017 analysis in *Newsweek* found that 12% of those who voted for Sanders in the Democratic primary voted for Trump in the general election, a lower proportion than that of Clinton supporters in 2008 who voted for John McCain.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In July 2016, a leak of the Democratic National Committee's emails appeared to show DNC officials favoring Clinton over Sanders.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Staff repeatedly discussed making his irreligious tendencies a potential campaign issue in southern states and questioned his party loyalty.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] DNC chair Debbie Wasserman Schultz called his campaign manager "an *ass*" and "a damn liar".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Speaking with Jake Tapper on CNN, Sanders responded to the leak, saying, "it is an outrage and sad that you would have people in important positions in the DNC trying to undermine my campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] It goes without saying: the function of the DNC is to represent all of the candidates—to be fair and even-minded.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] After the final primary election, Clinton became the presumptive Democratic nominee.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On July 12, Sanders formally endorsed Clinton.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He said he would continue to work with the Democratic National Convention organizers to implement progressive positions.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders refused to formally concede before the convention.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He spoke at the 2016 Democratic National Convention on July 25, during which he gave Clinton his full support.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Some of his supporters attempted to protest Clinton's nomination and booed when Sanders called for party unity.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He responded, "Our job is to do two things: to defeat Donald Trump and to elect Hillary Clinton ...
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On November 8, in the general election, Sanders received almost 6% of the vote in Vermont, even though he was no longer a candidate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] This was the highest share of a statewide presidential vote for a write-in draft campaign in American history.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He also received more votes in Vermont than Gary Johnson, the Libertarian candidate, and Jill Stein, the Green candidate, combined.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] It was possible to vote for Sanders as a write-in candidate in 12 states, and exact totals of write-in votes for him were published in three of them: California, New Hampshire, and Vermont.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In those three states, he received 111,850 write-in votes, about 15% of the write-in votes nationwide, and less than 1% of total nationwide vote.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In November 2016, Sanders's book *Our Revolution: A Future to Believe In* was released; upon its release, it was number three on *The New York Times* Best Seller list.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The audiobook later received a Grammy nomination for Best Spoken Word Album.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In February 2017, he began webcasting *The Bernie Sanders Show* on Facebook live streaming.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] As of April 2, 2017, guests had included William Barber, Josh Fox, Jane Mayer, and Bill Nye.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Polls taken in 2017 found him to be the most popular politician in the United States.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In February 2018, Special Counsel Robert Mueller's investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 US elections concluded that Russians had communicated false information during the primary campaigns to help Sanders and Stein and harm Clinton.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders rejected the investigation's conclusion, saying that he had seen no evidence that Russians had helped his campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Furthermore, he questioned the Clinton campaign's lack of action to prevent Russian interference.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He later said that his campaign had taken action to prevent Russian meddling in the election and that a campaign staffer had alerted the Clinton campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] *Politico* noted that a Sanders campaign volunteer contacted a political action committee (PAC) that supported the Clinton campaign to report suspicious activities but that the Sanders campaign did not contact the Clinton campaign as such.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Analysts have suggested that Sanders's campaign shifted both the Clinton campaign and the Democratic Party politically leftward.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] A new political organization, Brand New Congress, was formed in April 2016 by former campaign staffers.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] It works to elect congressional representatives with platforms in line with Sanders.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In August 2016, he formed Our Revolution, a political organization dedicated to educating voters about issues, getting people involved in the political process, and electing progressive candidates for local, state, and national office.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders's presidential campaigns led to a resurgence of interest in social democracy and democratic socialism among millennials.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On February 19, 2019, Sanders announced that he would seek the Democratic Party's 2020 nomination for president.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He had declined the Vermont Democratic Party nomination for U.S.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Senate in 2006, 2012, and 2018, which caused an unsuccessful legal challenge to his candidacy for the Democratic presidential nomination in 2016.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Along with his 2019 campaign announcement, he said he would abide by a new Democratic Party rule for presidential candidates and that he would affirm his membership in that party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On March 5, 2019, he signed a formal statement, known as a "loyalty pledge", that he is a member of the Democratic Party and will serve as a Democrat if elected.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] News reports noted that the day before, he had signed paperwork to run as an independent for reelection to his Senate seat in 2024.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders's campaign manager was Faiz Shakir.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The campaign's national co-chairs were Ben & Jerry's co-founder Ben Cohen, Representative Ro Khanna, Our Revolution president Nina Turner, and San Juan mayor Carmen Yulín Cruz.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Given the high national profile that Sanders maintained since his 2016 campaign, NPR described him as "no longer an underdog" when he announced his 2020 campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Using the large email list it built during the 2016 campaign, the 2020 campaign recruited more than one million volunteers within weeks of its launch.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] It enlisted several former NowThis News employees to produce professional videos for wide social media distribution, live-streamed various forums to its millions of social media followers, and launched a podcast and smartphone app for grassroots organizing.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders's 2020 campaign employed many of the same methods as its 2016 counterpart, eschewing a Super PAC and relying predominantly on small-dollar contributions.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] According to Federal Election Commission filings, the Sanders campaign had raised the most money in the 2020 Democratic field as of June 2019, including money left over from his 2018 Senate and 2016 presidential races.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In September 2019, the Sanders campaign became the fastest in US history to reach one million donors.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On October 1, 2019, the campaign announced it had raised $25.3 million in the year's third quarter, with an average donation of $18.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] It was the largest quarterly sum raised by any Democratic candidate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The campaign raised $34.5 million during the fourth quarter of 2019.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders steadily polled between 15% and 20% on most national surveys between May and September 2019, according to the RealClearPolitics average.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] This placed him in a decisive second-place behind Joe Biden until Elizabeth Warren and Kamala Harris caught up in July.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] From mid-February 2020 to the start of March, Sanders polled in first place in the Democratic primary ahead of Joe Biden and was described by the press as the party's presidential front-runner.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] According to a RealClearPolitics analysis, Sanders received the third-most mentions on CNN, Fox News, and MSNBC between January and August 2019, trailing only Joe Biden and Kamala Harris.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Biden, however, received twice as many mentions as Sanders and Harris.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Mentions of Sanders on *ABC World News Tonight* found him in second place, though also trailing Biden by a large margin.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Online mentions "reflect a slightly more balanced picture", with both Sanders and Elizabeth Warren running "neck-and-neck" with Biden.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On April 6, 2019, Sanders participated in a Fox News town hall that attracted more than 2.55 million viewers.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His decision to appear on Fox was controversial, given the Democratic National Committee's decision not to allow Fox to host any of its debates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His appearance saw an increase of Fox News viewers by 24% overall and 40% in the 25-to-54-year-old demographic, surpassing the ratings of all other Democratic presidential candidate town halls that year.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] As of September 2019, the town hall had received more than 1.5 million views on YouTube.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On August 6, 2019, Sanders appeared on *The Joe Rogan Experience* podcast.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Some praised Rogan for "hosting a pragmatic discussion" while others "seemed rather stunned by Sanders's decision to appear on the show at all".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] After the podcast, Rogan became a top-trending Twitter topic.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] After interviewing him, Rogan said, "I am not right-wing ...
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Bernie Sanders made a ton of sense to me and I would 100% vote for him." As of October 2019, the podcast had received more than ten million views on YouTube.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In December 2018, the Democratic National Committee (DNC) announced the preliminary schedule for 12 official DNC-sanctioned debates, set to begin in June 2019, with six in 2019 and the remaining six during the first four months of 2020.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] During the July and September debates, commentators described Sanders and Elizabeth Warren as having a "non-aggression pact", staking out similar progressive positions in contrast to the more conservative candidates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In the October 15 debate, his first appearance since his heart attack, debate coach Todd Graham gave Sanders's performance an A, his highest rating of all the candidates.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] CNN hosted the first 2020 debate in January with six candidates remaining.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Co-moderator Abby Phillip questioned Sanders and Warren about an allegation Warren had made that he had privately told her that a woman could not defeat Donald Trump.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Phillip asked Sanders, "Senator Sanders, CNN reported yesterday, and Senator Warren confirmed in a statement, that in 2018 you told her that you did not believe that a woman could win the election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders announced that he was suspending his campaign on April 8, 2020.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He stated that he would remain on the ballot in the remaining states and continue to accumulate delegates with the goal of influencing the Democratic Party's platform.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Biden responded, "I think that your endorsement means a great deal.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] I think people are going to be surprised that we are apart on some issues but we're awfully close on a whole bunch of others.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] A self-described democratic socialist, Sanders is a progressive and left-wing populist who admires social democratic programs in Europe and supports workplace democracy via union democracy, worker cooperatives, and workers' management of public enterprises.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He is a strong critic of contemporary neoliberal capitalism, which he calls "uber-capitalism", blaming it for such social ills as declining life expectancy and rising diseases of despair.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He advocates universal, single-payer healthcare, paid parental leave, and tuition-free tertiary education.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He supports lowering the cost of drugs by reforming patent laws to allow cheaper generic versions to be sold in the US.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He supported the Affordable Care Act, though he said it did not go far enough.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In November 2015, he gave a speech at Georgetown University about his view of democratic socialism, including its place in the policies of presidents Franklin D.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Based on his positions and votes throughout his career, many commentators consider his political platform primarily focused on tax-funded social benefits inspired by the Nordic model and not on social ownership of the means of production.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Some socialists and major socialist organizations have described Sanders as a democratic socialist, market socialist, or reformist socialist, while others have called him a reformist social democrat.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders views global warming as a serious problem, and advocates bold action to reverse its effects.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He calls for substantial investment in infrastructure, with energy efficiency, sustainability, and job creation as prominent goals.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He considers climate change the greatest threat to national security.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He said that family planning can help fight climate change.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He has become a prominent supporter of laws requiring companies to give their workers parental leave, sick leave, and vacation time, noting that nearly all other developed countries have such laws.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He also supports legislation that would make it easier for workers to join or form a trade union.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Believing greater emphasis is needed on labor rights and environmental concerns when negotiating international trade agreements, Sanders voted against and has long spoken against NAFTA, CAFTA, and PNTR with China.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He has called them a "disaster for the American worker", saying that they have resulted in American corporations moving abroad.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He also opposes the Trans-Pacific Partnership, which he says was "written by corporate America and the pharmaceutical industry and Wall Street." On May 1, 2019, he tweeted: "Since the China trade deal I voted against, America has lost over three million manufacturing jobs.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders also strongly opposes outsourcing American jobs.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] During discussions of the United States Innovation and Competition Act, which was to be used to fund the manufacture of semiconductors amid a shortage, he proposed a measure to ensure the companies the bill funded could not outsource their jobs.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The proposed measure would also block the companies from forbidding their employees to unionize.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders's proposal was voted down by most Democrats and all Republicans in the Senate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Ahead of the 2022 midterms, Sanders said he wants the Democratic Party to focus more on supporting unionization: "I think we should move to a system where, if 50% of the workers in a bargaining unit plus one vote to form a union, they have a union.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 1987, Sanders defined democracy as public ownership and workers' self-management in the workplace, saying: "Democracy means public ownership of the major means of production, it means decentralization, it means involving people in their work.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders supports reducing military spending while pursuing more diplomacy and international cooperation.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He opposed funding the Nicaraguan rebels known as the contras in the CIA's covert war against Nicaragua's leftist government.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He opposed the US invasion of Iraq and has criticized a number of policies instituted during the war on terror, particularly that of mass surveillance and the USA Patriot Act.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He criticized Israel's actions during the 2014 Gaza war and US involvement in the Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On November 15, 2015, in response to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL)'s attacks in Paris, he cautioned against Islamophobia and said, "We gotta be tough, not stupid" in the war against ISIL, adding that the US should continue to welcome Syrian refugees.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He criticized the January 2020 drone assassination of Iranian general Qasem Soleimani, calling it a dangerous escalation of tensions that could lead to an expensive war.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders supports Palestinian rights and has often criticized Israel, while consistently supporting Israel's right to exist.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 2020, he called the American Israel Public Affairs Committee a platform for bigotry and said he would not attend its conference.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He first called for only a pause in fighting, saying that he "doesn't know if a ceasefire is possible with an organization like Hamas", but later called for a humanitarian ceasefire and urged Biden to withhold military aid to Israel.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders accused Israel of mass starvation, ethnic cleansing, and extermination.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders initially said that allegations of genocide had to be adjudicated by the International Court of Justice, but in September 2025 he said: "The intent is clear.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Addressing Westminster College in a September 2017 speech, Sanders laid out a foreign policy plan for greater international collaboration, adherence to US-led international agreements such as the Paris Agreement and the Iran nuclear deal framework and promoting human rights and democratic ideals.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He emphasized the consequences associated with global economic inequality and climate change and urged reining in the use of US military power, saying it "must always be a last resort".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He also criticized US support for "murderous regimes" during the Cold War, such as those in Iran, Chile and El Salvador and said that those actions continue to make the US less safe.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He also spoke critically of Russian interference in the 2016 US elections and the way President Trump has handled the crisis.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He does not consider Turkey a US ally and condemned the Turkish military offensive against US-aligned Kurdish forces in northeastern Syria.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders supports closing the "gun show loophole", banning assault weapons, and passing and enforcing universal federal background checks for gun purchases.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 1990, his bid to become a US Representative benefitted from the National Rifle Association of America opposing the competing campaign of Peter Smith, who had reversed his stance on firearm restrictions, and waiting periods for handgun purchases.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 1996, he voted against additional funding to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention for research on issues related to firearms, but in 2016, he called for an increase in CDC funding for the study of gun violence.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On social issues, Sanders has long taken progressive stances.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He considers himself a feminist, is pro-choice on abortion, and opposes defunding Planned Parenthood.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He has long advocated for LGBT rights; in 2009, he supported legalizing same-sex marriage in Vermont.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders has denounced institutional racism and called for criminal justice reform to reduce the number of people in prison, advocates a crackdown on police brutality, and supports abolishing private, for-profit prisons and the death penalty.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He also supports legalizing marijuana at the federal level.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He has advocated for greater democratic participation by citizens, campaign finance reform, and a constitutional amendment or judicial decision that would overturn *Citizens United v.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders criticized President Trump for appointing multiple billionaires to his cabinet.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He criticized Trump's rolling back President Obama's Clean Power Plan, noting the scientifically reported effect on climate change of human activity and citing Trump's calling those reports a hoax.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He called for caution on the Syrian Civil War, saying, "It's easier to get into a war than out of one." In 2017, he promised to defeat "Trump and Trumpism and the Republican right-wing ideology".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders gave an online reply to Trump's January 2018 State of the Union address in which he called Trump "compulsively dishonest" and criticized him for initiating "a looming immigration crisis" by ending the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He voiced concern about Trump's failure to mention the finding that Russia had interfered in the 2016 election and "will likely interfere in the 2018 midterms we will be holding ...
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Unless you have a very special relationship with Mr.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On January 6, 2021, Trump supporters attacked the United States Capitol.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders voted to convict Trump on both articles of his first impeachment trial in 2020 (for pressuring a foreign leader to investigate Joe Biden), and again on the sole article of his second impeachment trial in 2021 (for inciting the Capitol attack).
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders influenced the environmental policy goals of the Biden administration as described before Biden's nomination.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Biden's policy team adopted certain details from the Biden–Sanders Unity Task Forces' climate recommendations.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] After Biden was elected president, Sanders became the subject of speculation over a potential appointment as Labor Secretary, which was supported by several progressive groups, such as the Sunrise Movement.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] For his part, Sanders said that he would accept Biden's nomination if it was offered, but Boston mayor Marty Walsh was chosen for the position instead.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] When announcing Walsh's nomination, Biden confirmed that he had discussed the position with Sanders, but the two agreed that Sanders's resignation from the Senate and the ensuing special election would have put the Democrats' slim Senate majority at risk.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On February 23, 2021, Sanders became the first senator in the Democratic caucus to oppose one of Biden's cabinet picks when he voted against Tom Vilsack's confirmation as Agriculture Secretary, citing concerns about Vilsack's past work as a lobbyist and ties to large corporations.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 2022, Sanders signed letters to Vilsack and Solicitor General of the United States Elizabeth Prelogar asking them to support the California farm animal welfare law Proposition 12 against a challenge to the law the National Pork Producers Council filed before the Supreme Court.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders strongly supported Senate Democrats' decision to use budget reconciliation, a procedure used to avoid filibusters, to pass the American Rescue Plan Act of 2021, despite having criticized Republicans' use of reconciliation to pass the 2017 tax cuts.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] The bill passed the Senate by a 50–49 vote and was signed into law by Biden on March 11, 2021.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders has continued to have a strong influence on the Biden administration.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] A few days before the 2022 United States elections, Sanders said he regarded them as deciding the fate of democracy, abortion, and climate change, calling them the "most consequential" midterm elections of modern US history.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He expressed fear that the Democratic Party had "not done a good enough job" of getting its message out "to young people and working-class people".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders was the only independent or Democratic senator to oppose the CHIPS and Science Act, joining 17 Republican senators.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In April 2023, Sanders endorsed Biden in the 2024 United States presidential election, and after Biden withdrew from the race, Sanders endorsed Harris for president at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders attempted to appeal to pro-Palestinian critics of Harris by saying, "I promise you, after Kamala wins, we will together do everything that we can to change US policy toward Netanyahu", and emphasizing Donald Trump's policies on climate change, minimum wage, and tax cuts for the wealthy.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Trump's reelection in 2024 was met with consternation by Democrats.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] After Trump won the election, Sanders released a statement blaming the Democratic Party's abandonment of "working-class people" for its defeat.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In February 2025, Sanders began the "Fighting Oligarchy Tour", in which he and Ocasio-Cortez held rallies criticizing Trump's policies and economic inequality.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In April 2025, Sanders criticized the administration, saying that its moving "rapidly toward oligarchy", he also called US a "pseudo-democracy".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] At one rally held in June 2025, Sanders reacted to news of Trump's bombing of Iranian nuclear sites by saying: "The American people are being lied to again today.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] We cannot allow history to repeat itself".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Also in June, Sanders endorsed progressive politician and DSA member Zohran Mamdani for the 2025 New York City Democratic mayoral primary, calling him "best choice" for mayor.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In September 2025, Sanders criticized Democratic Party officials for their perceived refusal to support Mamdani after his victory in the New York City mayoral primary.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In the same month, Sanders gave an interview to Mamdani in which they discussed Sanders's political beginnings and his achievements as a mayor and senator.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] On September 15, 2025, Sanders said that Israel is committing genocide in Gaza, becoming the first US senator to make such comment.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In early February 2026, he criticized the U.S. government's proposed military aid to Israel.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In a post on social media, he wrote that the U.S. was planning to send approximately $7 billion in weapons to Israel.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders argued that the U.S. should prioritize domestic needs, such as healthcare for all Americans, rather than provide military assistance to Israel.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In April 2026, he proposed a resolution to block certain military aid to Israel, which failed.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Born into a Democratic-voting family, Sanders was first introduced to political activism when his brother Larry joined the Young Democrats of America and campaigned for Adlai Stevenson II in 1956.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders joined Vermont's Liberty Union Party in 1971 and was a candidate for several offices, never coming close to winning election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He became party chairman, but quit in 1977 to become an independent.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 1980, he served as an elector for the Socialist Workers Party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In 1981, Sanders ran as an independent for mayor of Burlington, Vermont, and defeated the Democratic incumbent; he was reelected three times.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Although an independent, he endorsed Democratic presidential candidates Walter Mondale in 1984 and Jesse Jackson in 1988.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His endorsement of Mondale was lukewarm (telling reporters that "if you go around saying that Mondale would be a great president, you would be a liar and a hypocrite"), but he supported Jackson enthusiastically.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] *The Washington Post* reported that the Jackson campaign helped inspire Sanders to work more closely with the Democratic Party.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders attended the 1983 conference of the Socialist Party USA where he gave a speech.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders first ran for the US House of Representatives in 1988 and for the US Senate in 2006, often adopting a strategy of winning the Democratic Party primary, thereby eliminating Democratic challengers, and then running as an independent in the general election.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He continued this strategy through his reelection in the 2018 United States Senate election in Vermont.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Throughout his tenure in Congress, he has been listed as an independent.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He caucused with Democrats in the House while refusing to join the party, and continues to caucus with Democrats in the Senate.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Some conservative southern House Democrats initially barred him from the caucus as they believed that allowing a self-described socialist to join would harm their electoral prospects.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He soon came to work constructively with Democrats, voting with the party over 90% of the time during his tenure in Congress.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Starting with his 2016 presidential campaign, Sanders's announcements suggested that not only was he running as a Democrat, but that he would run as a Democrat in future elections.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] In October 2017, Sanders said he would run for reelection as an independent in 2018 despite pressure to run as a Democrat.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] His party status became ambiguous again in March 2019 when he signed a formal "loyalty pledge" to the Democratic Party stating that he was a member of the party and would serve as a Democrat if elected president.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] He signed the pledge the day after he signed paperwork to run as an independent for reelection to the Senate in 2024.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p02] Sanders is one of two independents in the Senate, along with Angus King, both of whom caucus with the Democrats.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In 1963, Sanders and Deborah Shiling Messing, whom he met in college, volunteered for several months on the Israeli kibbutz Sha'ar HaAmakim.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] They married in 1964 and bought a summer home in Vermont; they had no children and divorced in 1966.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] His son (and only biological child), Levi Sanders, was born in 1969 to then-girlfriend Susan Campbell Mott.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] On May 28, 1988, Sanders married Jane O'Meara Driscoll (née Mary Jane O'Meara), who later became president of Burlington College, in Burlington, Vermont.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] The day after their wedding, the couple visited the Soviet Union as part of an official delegation in his capacity as mayor.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] They own a row house in Capitol Hill, a house in Burlington's New North End neighborhood, and a lakefront summer home in North Hero.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] He considers Jane's three children—Dave Driscoll (born 1975), Carina Driscoll (born 1974), and Heather Titus (née Driscoll; 1971)—to be his own.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Sanders's elder brother, Larry, lives in England; he was a Green Party county councillor, representing the East Oxford division on Oxfordshire County Council, until he retired from the council in 2013.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Larry ran as a Green Party candidate for Oxford West and Abingdon in the 2015 British general election and came in fifth.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Bernie Sanders told CNN, "I owe my brother an enormous amount.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] On October 1, 2019, Sanders was hospitalized after experiencing chest pains at a campaign event in Las Vegas.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] His campaign announced the next day that a blockage had been found in one coronary artery and two stents inserted.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Scheduled campaign events and appearances were canceled until further notice.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Two days later his campaign released a statement that he had been diagnosed with a heart attack.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] He was released from the hospital the same day.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In December 2019, three months after the heart attack, Sanders released letters from three physicians, Attending Physician of Congress Brian P.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Monahan and two cardiologists, who declared Sanders healthy and recovered from his heart condition.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] On December 4, 2015, Sanders won *Time*'s 2015 Person of the Year readers' poll with 10.2% of the vote but did not receive the editorial board's award.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] On March 20, 2016, he was given an honorary Lushootseed name, *dxʷshudičup*, by Deborah Parker in Seattle to honor his focus on Native American issues during his presidential campaign.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] On May 30, 2017, Sanders received an honorary degree of Doctor of Humane Letters from Brooklyn College.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Larry Sanders said of their parents, "They were very pleased to be Jews, but didn't have a strong belief in God." Bernie had a bar mitzvah at the historic Kingsway Jewish Center in Midwood, Brooklyn, where he grew up.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In 1963, in cooperation with the Labor Zionist youth movement Hashomer Hatzair, Sanders and his first wife volunteered at Sha'ar HaAmakim, a kibbutz in northern Israel.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] His motivation for the trip was as much socialistic as it was Zionistic.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] As mayor of Burlington, Sanders allowed a Chabad public menorah to be placed at city hall, an action the ACLU contested.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] He publicly inaugurated the Hanukkah menorah and performed the Jewish religious ritual of blessing Hanukkah candles.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] His early and strong support played a significant role in the now widespread public menorah celebrations around the globe.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] He describes himself as "not particularly religious" and "not actively involved" with organized religion.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] A press package issued by his office states his religion as Jewish.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] He has said he believes in God, but not necessarily in a traditional way: "I think everyone believes in God in their own ways", he said.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Sanders does not regularly attend synagogue, and he does not refrain from working on Rosh Hashanah, as observant Jews do.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] He has attended yahrzeit observances in memory of the deceased, for the father of a friend, and in 2015 attended a Tashlikh, an atonement ceremony, with the mayor of Lynchburg on the afternoon of Rosh Hashanah.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] According to Richard Sugarman, his Jewish identity is "certainly more ethnic and cultural than religious." His wife is Roman Catholic, and he has often expressed admiration for Pope Francis, saying that "the leader of the Catholic Church is raising profound issues.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] It is important that we listen to what he has said." He has said he feels very close to Francis's economic teachings, describing him as "incredibly smart and brave".
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In April 2016, he accepted an invitation from Marcelo Sánchez Sorondo, an aide close to Francis, to speak at a Vatican conference on economic and environmental issues.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] While at the Vatican, he met briefly with Francis.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In December 1987, during his tenure as mayor of Burlington, Sanders recorded a folk album, *We Shall Overcome*, with 30 Vermont musicians.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] As he was not a skilled singer, he performed his vocals in a talking blues style.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Owing to his two high-profile campaigns in the 2016 and 2020 Democratic primaries, Sanders and his campaigns have generated many Internet memes and other online content.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] The Facebook group Bernie Sanders' Dank Meme Stash, where users can submit memes focused around Sanders, received significant attention in the 2016 primary season due to the at-the-time unique idea of a meme community focused entirely on a politician.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] During the 2020 primary season, a still from a fundraising video in which Sanders tells the viewers "I am once again asking for your financial support" went viral online, with numerous edits made of the frame.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] The day before Super Tuesday 2020, a video of the Twitch streamer Neekolul wearing a Bernie 2020 shirt and lip-syncing the song "Oki Doki Boomer" also went viral.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In 2021, a frame from the inauguration of Joe Biden showing Sanders seated in a folding chair wearing patterned mittens and a jacket reminiscent of the one in the "I am once again asking" meme went viral, with the image captioned or edited into other images, most commonly popular movie scenes.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] Sanders appeared in a cameo role in the 1988 comedy-drama film *Sweet Hearts Dance*, playing a man who distributes candy to young trick-or-treaters.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In 1999, he acted in the film *My X-Girlfriend's Wedding Reception*, playing Rabbi Manny Shevitz.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In this role, he mourned the Brooklyn Dodgers' move to Los Angeles, reflecting Sanders's own upbringing in Brooklyn.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] On February 6, 2016, he was a guest star alongside Larry David (who is a sixth cousin once removed of Sanders) on *Saturday Night Live*, playing a Polish immigrant on a steamship that was sinking near the Statue of Liberty.
[src:bernie-sanders/bernie-sanders-p03] In the DC Extended Universe film *Birds of Prey (and the Fantabulous Emancipation of One Harley Quinn)*, one of the reasons Roman Sionis wants Harley Quinn dead is that she "voted for Bernie".
